The SPDR S&P 500 trust (SPY) is used for the analysis and subsequent trading strategy of this project, because it comprises 500 large- and mid-cap U.S. stocks. These stocks are selected by a committee based on market size, liquidity, and industry. The S&P 500 serves as one of the main benchmarks of the U.S. equity market and indicates the financial health and stability of the economy (https://www.investopedia.com/articles/investing/122215/spy-spdr-sp-500-trust-etf.asp).

Second-level price data for SPY were extracted from TD Ameritrade, using a wrapper of the broker's API.

The code can be found on my Github profile (https://github.com/GizDave).

Only the week of 5/10/2021 is used to lower the hardware constraint, but the framework should be scalable to a larger quantity of data.

Questions

  • What does the formation of candles tell us about price action?

  • Do the oscillations in the wicks and bodies matter?

  • What about the lengths of individual candle parts?

  • Can these elements be used to predict price movements?

(From here on, the candles being discussed have the following structure.)

There are 368997 time gaps, ranged from 0 to 63002 seconds. 114149 of which are more than 1 seconds apart and 6 are more than 5 seconds apart.

Besides the 5 gaps that are the results of transitioning from one trading day to another, the last gap happened on 5/14/2021 because of a connection error, in which the program tried to reconnect for about a minute.

The smaller gaps between data entries were due to network delays and the way TD Ameritrade structures it's real-time stream, which only sends new data.

Candle Creation¶

In [17]:
# create candles
def makeCandles(window):
  candles = history_core.copy()
  candles['HIGH_PRICE'] = candles.MID_PRICE
  candles['OPEN_PRICE'] = candles.MID_PRICE
  candles['CLOSE_PRICE'] = candles.MID_PRICE
  candles['LOW_PRICE'] = candles.MID_PRICE

  return candles.groupby(candles.index.date).resample(window).agg({
      # candle components
      'HIGH_PRICE': lambda x: x.max(),
      'OPEN_PRICE': lambda x: x.head(1),
      'CLOSE_PRICE': lambda x: x.tail(1),
      'LOW_PRICE': lambda x: x.min(),
      # custom components
      'BID_PRICE': lambda x: x.mean(),
      'ASK_PRICE': lambda x: x.mean(),
      'BID_SIZE': lambda x: x.sum(),
      'ASK_SIZE': lambda x: x.sum()
  }).droplevel(0)
In [18]:
# calculate the time spent in wicks and in the body
def getTime(candle):
  row = pd.Series({
    'BODY_TIME': candle[
      (candle.MID_PRICE >= candle[['CLOSE_PRICE', 'OPEN_PRICE']].min(axis=1)) & 
      (candle.MID_PRICE <= candle[['CLOSE_PRICE', 'OPEN_PRICE']].max(axis=1))
    ].TIMESTAMP.count(),
    'UPPER_WICK_TIME': candle[
      (candle.MID_PRICE > candle[['CLOSE_PRICE', 'OPEN_PRICE']].max(axis=1)) & 
      (candle.MID_PRICE <= candle.HIGH_PRICE)
    ].TIMESTAMP.count(),
    'LOWER_WICK_TIME': candle[
      (candle.MID_PRICE < candle[['CLOSE_PRICE', 'OPEN_PRICE']].min(axis=1)) & 
      (candle.MID_PRICE >= candle.LOW_PRICE)
     ].TIMESTAMP.count()
  })

  return row

def getTimes(candles):
  history_core['temp'] = history_core.index.to_series().apply(lambda t: t.replace(second=0))
  temp = history_core.reset_index()[['temp', 'TIMESTAMP', 'MID_PRICE']].merge(
    candles[['HIGH_PRICE', 'OPEN_PRICE', 'CLOSE_PRICE', 'LOW_PRICE']], 
    left_on = history_core.temp, 
    right_on = candles.index
  ).drop(columns=['key_0'])
  candles_time = temp.groupby(temp['temp']).apply(lambda x: getTime(x))

  candles['BODY_TIME'] = candles_time['BODY_TIME']
  candles['UPPER_WICK_TIME'] = candles_time['UPPER_WICK_TIME']
  candles['LOWER_WICK_TIME'] = candles_time['LOWER_WICK_TIME']
In [19]:
# calculate body lengths, wick lengths
def getLengths(candles):
  candles['HEIGHT'] = candles['HIGH_PRICE'] - candles['LOW_PRICE']
  candles['HEIGHT_CHG'] = candles['HEIGHT'].diff()
  candles['BODY_LEN'] = abs(candles.CLOSE_PRICE - candles.OPEN_PRICE)
  candles['UPPER_WICK_LEN'] = candles.apply(lambda x: x.HIGH_PRICE - x.CLOSE_PRICE if x.CLOSE_PRICE > x.OPEN_PRICE else x.HIGH_PRICE - x.OPEN_PRICE, axis=1)
  candles['LOWER_WICK_LEN'] = candles.apply(lambda x: x.CLOSE_PRICE - x.LOW_PRICE if x.CLOSE_PRICE < x.OPEN_PRICE else x.OPEN_PRICE - x.LOW_PRICE, axis=1)
In [20]:
# normalize based on candle height
def normLengths(candles):
  candles['BODY_LEN'] = candles['BODY_LEN'] / candles['HEIGHT']
  candles['BODY_LEN_CHG'] = candles['BODY_LEN'].diff()
  candles['UPPER_WICK_LEN'] = candles['UPPER_WICK_LEN'] / candles['HEIGHT']
  candles['UPPER_WICK_LEN_CHG'] = candles['UPPER_WICK_LEN'].diff()
  candles['LOWER_WICK_LEN'] = candles['LOWER_WICK_LEN'] / candles['HEIGHT']
  candles['LOWER_WICK_LEN_CHG'] = candles['LOWER_WICK_LEN'].diff()
In [21]:
# calculate wick ratios relative to the bodies
def getRatios(candles):
  candles['UPPER_WICK_RATIO'] = candles['UPPER_WICK_LEN'] / candles['BODY_LEN'] # upper wick to body
  candles['UPPER_WICK_RATIO_CHG'] = candles['UPPER_WICK_RATIO'].diff()
  candles['LOWER_WICK_RATIO'] = candles['LOWER_WICK_LEN'] / candles['BODY_LEN'] # lower wick to body
  candles['LOWER_WICK_RATIO_CHG'] = candles['LOWER_WICK_RATIO'].diff()
  candles['WICK_RATIO'] = (candles['UPPER_WICK_LEN'] + candles['LOWER_WICK_LEN']) / candles['BODY_LEN'] # wick to body
  candles['WICK_RATIO_CHG'] = candles['WICK_RATIO'].diff()
In [22]:
# calculate returns
def getReturns(candles):
  # assume the open price matches the actual previous close price
  candles['return'] = (candles['CLOSE_PRICE'] - candles['OPEN_PRICE']) / candles['OPEN_PRICE']
In [23]:
def wrapper(timeframe):
  candles = makeCandles(timeframe)
  getLengths(candles)
  normLengths(candles)
  getRatios(candles)
  getTimes(candles)
  getReturns(candles)
  candles.replace([np.inf, -np.inf], np.nan, inplace=True)
  return candles
In [24]:
# create candles with proposed features using 3 different time frames

# 30s 
candles_30s = wrapper('30S')

# 1min
candles_1min = wrapper("1Min")

candles_5min = wrapper('5Min')

    • It might be helpful to use shorter time frame as a reference.

Multivariate Analysis¶

Variables are not scaled because the distribution is not known, but note the large differences between the variables' variances, especially between those of bid/ask sizes and others, which will influence the results of PCA.

There are missing values inside the dataframes, but imputations are not performed to preserve the data. Instead, the rows with missing values are dropped.

In [32]:
def pca_summary(pca, data):
    names = data.columns
    a = list(np.std(pca.transform(data), axis=0))
    b = list(pca.explained_variance_ratio_)
    c = [np.sum(pca.explained_variance_ratio_[:i]) for i in range(1, len(pca.explained_variance_ratio_)+1)]
    summary = pd.DataFrame(zip(a, b, c), index=names, columns=["Std", "Explained Variance", "Cumulative Variance"])
    summary['Explained Variance'] = summary['Explained Variance'].round(decimals=4)
    display(summary)
In [33]:
def elbow(pca, data):
    y = np.std(pca.transform(data), axis=0)**2
    x = np.arange(len(y)) + 1
    plt.plot(x, y, "o-")
    plt.xticks(x, [str(i) for i in x], rotation=60)
    plt.ylabel("Variance")
    plt.show()

Use Principal Component Analysis to find what features to use.

The features to use are HEIGHT, HEIGHT_CHG, BODY_LEN, UPPER_WICK_LEN.

Modeling¶

This strategy aims to predict the beginning of breakouts. It's best to be used a warning system of a larger model that incorporates indicators/features for longer-term price action.

X = ['HEIGHT', 'HEIGHT_CHG', 'BODY_LEN', 'UPPER_WICK_LEN']
y = ['MID_PRICE']
In [40]:
# create train/test datasets
# use candles constructed with time frames from 30s to 5min in 30s increment
s = 30 # seconds
test_size = 0.2

candles_collection = {}

for i in range(10):
  label = '{}Min'.format(s/60)
  df_x = wrapper(label).dropna() # drop rows with missing values
  df_x['MID_PRICE'] = (df_x['HIGH_PRICE'] + df_x['LOW_PRICE'])/2 # might be distorted by long wicks
  df_x = df_x[X + y]
  X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(df_x[X], df_x[y], test_size=test_size, random_state=None)
  candles_collection[label] = [X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test]
  s = s + 30

  # record model
  linear_collection[label] = linear

K-Nearest Neighbor¶

In [43]:
# K-Nearest Neighbor to emulate the breakout system
max_neigh = 10 # limited to 10 for hardware constraints

knn_collection = {label: [] for label in candles_collection.keys()}

for label, candles in candles_collection.items():
  for n in range(1, max_neigh+1):
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = candles_collection[label]
    # modeling
    neigh = KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=n)
    neigh.fit(X_train, y_train)
    # record model
    knn_collection[label].append(neigh)

Ensemble Learning¶

In [54]:
# Combine K-Nearest Neighbor and Support Vector Machine
def ensemble(data):
  knn = best_model['KNN'].predict(data).flatten()
  svm = best_model['SVM'].predict(data)
  df = pd.DataFrame(data={'KNN': knn, 'SVM': svm})
  return df.mean(axis=1)
In [55]:
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = candles_collection[label]
y_pred = ensemble(X_test)
en_mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)

Investment Strategy¶

  • Use past N candles for KNN and the most recent candle for SVM
    • N=10 and use 4.5Min as the time frame from the results of KNN
  • Combine the results through ensemble learning
  • Compared the predicted MID_PRICE with the current MID_PRICE.
  • If the predicted price trends up, go long. Otherwise, go short.
